    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Soft, yellowish-gray wood with a coarse grain from the species Juglans cinerea, ranging in color from light chestnut brown with darker zones in the heartwood to pale yellow or white in the sapwood. It polishes well and has been used for carving, furniture, and interior millwork</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047822/MFA Conservation and Art Material Encyclopedia Online: CAMEO (2005-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Nogal liviano y suave de color marrón castaño claro con zonas más oscuras en el duramen a amarillo pálido o blanco en la albura. Se ha utilizado en muebles, adornos interiores y carpintería en general.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Lichtgewicht, zacht notenhout, variërend in kleur van licht hazelnootbruin met donkere gedeelten in het kernhout tot lichtgeel of wit in het spinthout. Het werd gebruikt voor meubilair, afwerking binnenshuis en in het algemeen voor fijn timmerwerk.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
